## What is adjusted plus-minus?

Plus-minus is a sport statistics used to measure a player’s impact on difference between their team’s total scoring versus their opponent’s.  For example, while player A is on the court, his team scores 10 more points than his opponent’s team. Then player A’s and his/her teammates’ plus-minus is +10. Although the statistic was pioneered in the sport of hockey, it has found its way into use in other sports and areas of life. For instance, basketball.

Adjusted plus-minus is an advanced statistics in basketball games which is often regarded as a better one than plus-minus.  The main goal of adjusted plus-minus is to infect individual impact of a player.

## Differences between plus-minus and adjusted plus-minus

So, why don’t we use plus-minus? Well, an example will be a great answer of this question.  As we all know, LeBron James is the greatest basketball player in the world and his team, Miami Heat, is one of the best team in the world. Let’s call it LeBron factor. Due to the LeBron factor, Mario Chalmers’ plus-minus is +14.0(2012-2013 regular season) which is higher than Carmelo Anthony’s +5.7. But Carmelo is a better player. Since the plus-minus cannot tell us that Carmelo Anthony is a better player than Mario Chalmers, we need a better statistic, the adjusted plus-minus.

There are two models to specify the statistic and both of them are based on the weighted least-squares. The first model is invented by Rosenbaum in 2004 and the second model is invented by Ilardy and Barzilai in 2008. In this article, both of two models will be presented and the results of them will be analyzed.

The data in this article comes from www.basketballvalues.com and www.basketball-reference.com .

## Rosenbaum model

The main idea of this model is shown below.

$$Margin = \beta_1 X_1 + ... + \beta_n X_n + \epsilon$$

* $Margin$ means 100 * (Home team points per possession – Away tam points per possession)

* $β_k$ means the coefficients of the regression

* $X_k$ will be 1 if player k plays for the home team and it will be -1 if player k plays for the away team. Otherwise, it will be zero

* $\epsilon$ is the error

We take $β_k$ as the pure adjusted plus-minus (that is, papm) of player k. If player k’s papm is 10 then when he is on the court, his team will get 10 more points per 100 possessions rather than an average player in the league on the court.

The result is shown below:

PAPM

![papm-1](data:image/jpg;base64,)

It turns out the result is pretty noisy because the standard errors of the coefficients are big if we just use one season’s data. So I use multiple seasons’ data and the weights of three seasons are 1, 0.5 and 0.25 respectively.

Here is the data I used:

![papm-2](data:image/png;base64,)

There are two more steps in this model originally, but the pure adjusted plus-minus is the most widely used statistic.

## Ilardy-Barzilai model

The model is presented by Ilardy and Barzilai in 2008. The algorithm is shown below.

$$Margin = \beta_1 X_1 + ... + \beta_n X_n + \delta_1 D_1 + ... + \delta_k D_k + \epsilon$$

* Margin is exactly what has mentioned above.

* $X_i$ equals to 1 when player I is on offense during observation. Otherwise, $X_i$ equals to 0.

* $D_i$ equals to 1 when player I is on defense during observation. Otherwise, $D_i$ equals to 0.

We take $\beta_i$ as the offensive adjusted plus-minus of player I and $\delta_i$ as the opposite of defensive adjusted plus-minus of player i. The adjusted plus-minus would be oapm + dapm. If player A’s opam is 5 and his dpma is 5, then the team with player A can score 5 more points than the same team with an average player instead of player A per 100 possessions and the opponent of the team with average player instead of player A can score 5 more points than the opponent of the team with player A per 100 possessions. That is, compared to an average player, player A can make his team outscores 10 points. This is what the adjusted plus-minus mean.

The result is shown below:

![papm-3](data:image/png;base64,)

## Conclusion

To be honest, the apm is just the first step. It still needs to be improved to be a good statistic.

![papm-4](data:image/png;base64,)

As you can see, the difference between two models is not that big. But personally, I prefer the second model because it looks more reasonable and it’s Std Errors are smaller.

So, the first step, huh? What’s the second step? It’s RAPM. Regularized  adjusted plus-minus. To be continued ...

## Code

Rosenbaum model:

```r
library(plyr)
matchup <- read.csv('matchup.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
player <- read.csv('player.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
matchup2 <- read.csv('matchup2.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
player2 <- read.csv('player2.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
matchup3 <- read.csv('matchup3.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
player3 <- read.csv('player3.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')

#turn the Inf values in matchup to the mean
dealna <- function(x){
    mean1 <- mean(na.omit(x$OffensiveRtgHome))
    mean2 <- mean(na.omit(x$OffensiveRtgAway))
    x$OffensiveRtgHome[is.na(x$OffensiveRtgHome)] = mean1
    x$OffensiveRtgAway[is.na(x$OffensiveRtgAway)] = mean2
    return(x)
}
matchup <- dealna(matchup)
matchup2 <- dealna(matchup2)
matchup3 <- dealna(matchup3)

#weighting
w1 <- rep(1, nrow(matchup))
w2 <- rep(0.5, nrow(matchup2))
w3 <- rep(0.25, nrow(matchup3))
w <- c(w1, w2, w3)

matchup <- rbind(matchup, matchup2)
matchup <- rbind(matchup, matchup3)

playercreat <- function(a) {
    a <- a[-which(a$SimpleMin < 500), c(1, 2)]
    return(a)
}

player <- playercreat(player)
player2 <- playercreat(player2)
player3 <- playercreat(player3)


player <- merge(player, player2, by = 'PlayerID', all.x = TRUE, all.y = TRUE)
player <- merge(player, player3, by = 'PlayerID', all.x = TRUE, all.y = TRUE)


player <- na.omit(player)
player <- player[, -3]
colnames(player)[2] <- 'PlayerTrueName'

c <- matchup[, c(6:15)]
mat <- matrix(data= NA, ncol = nrow(player), nrow = nrow(c) + 1)
k <- player$PlayerID
mat[1, ] <- k


colnames(mat) <- player$PlayerTrueName
for(i in 1:nrow(c)){
    for(j in 1:5){
        mat[i+1, which(mat[1,] == c[i,j])] <- 1
    }
    for(j in 6:ncol(c)){
        mat[i+1, which(mat[1,] == c[i,j])] <- -1
    }
}

mat[is.na(mat)] <- 0
mat <- mat[-1, ]

margin <- (matchup$OffensiveRtgHome - matchup$OffensiveRtgAway)
lm_data <- cbind(margin, mat)

lm_data <- data.frame(lm_data)
lm_model <- lm(margin~., data = lm_data, weights = w)
rapm <- lm_model$coefficients[-1]
name <- data.frame(player$PlayerTrueName)
name[,1] <- as.character(name[,1])
info <- cbind(name, rapm)
info <- na.omit(info)
con <- confint(lm_model, level = 0.95)
info <- info[order(info$rapm, decreasing = TRUE),]
```

Ilardy-Barzilai model:

```r
library(plyr)
matchup <- read.csv('matchup.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
player <- read.csv('player.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
matchup2 <- read.csv('matchup2.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
player2 <- read.csv('player2.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
matchup3 <- read.csv('matchup3.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')
player3 <- read.csv('player3.csv', na.strings = 'NULL')

#turn the Inf values in matchup to the mean
dealna <- function(x){
    mean1 <- mean(na.omit(x$OffensiveRtgHome))
    mean2 <- mean(na.omit(x$OffensiveRtgAway))
    x$OffensiveRtgHome[is.na(x$OffensiveRtgHome)] = mean1
    x$OffensiveRtgAway[is.na(x$OffensiveRtgAway)] = mean2
    return(x)
}
matchup <- dealna(matchup)
matchup2 <- dealna(matchup2)
matchup3 <- dealna(matchup3)

#weighting
w1 <- rep(1, nrow(matchup))
w2 <- rep(0.5, nrow(matchup2))
w3 <- rep(0.25, nrow(matchup3))
w <- c(w1, w2, w3)

matchup <- rbind(matchup, matchup2)
matchup <- rbind(matchup, matchup3)

playercreat <- function(a) {
    a <- a[-which(a$SimpleMin < 500), c(1, 2)]
    return(a)
}

player <- playercreat(player)
player2 <- playercreat(player2)
player3 <- playercreat(player3)


player <- merge(player, player2, by = 'PlayerID', all.x = TRUE, all.y = TRUE)
player <- merge(player, player3, by = 'PlayerID', all.x = TRUE, all.y = TRUE)


player <- na.omit(player)
player <- player[, -3]
colnames(player)[2] <- 'PlayerTrueName'

c <- matchup[, c(6:15)]
mat <- matrix(data= NA, ncol = nrow(player), nrow = nrow(c) + 1)
k <- player$PlayerID
mat[1, ] <- k


colnames(mat) <- player$PlayerTrueName
for(i in 1:nrow(c)){
    for(j in 1:5){
        mat[i+1, which(mat[1,] == c[i,j])] <- 1
    }
    for(j in 6:ncol(c)){
        mat[i+1, which(mat[1,] == c[i,j])] <- -1
    }
}

mat[is.na(mat)] <- 0
mat <- mat[-1, ]

margin <- c(matchup$OffensiveRtgHome, matchup$OffensiveRtgAway)
Xh <- mat
Da <- mat
colnames(Da) <- paste(colnames(Da), 1)
Xh[which(Xh == -1)] <- 0
Da[which(Da == 1)] <- 0
Da[which(Da == -1)] <- 1
dat <- rbind(cbind(Xh, Da), cbind(Da, Xh))
lm_data <- cbind(margin, dat)
lm_data <- as.data.frame(lm_data)
lm_model <- lm(margin~., data = lm_data)
pm <- lm_model$coefficients[-1]
opm <- pm[1:ncol(mat)]
dpm <- pm[222:length(pm)]
dpm <- -dpm
apm <- opm + dpm
names <- colnames(Xh)
info <- data.frame(names, opm, dpm, apm)
info <- info[order(info$apm, decreasing = TRUE), ]
```
